# postcss-auto-layer

[npm](https://www.npmjs.com/package/postcss-auto-layer)
[license](./LICENSE)

A [PostCSS](https://postcss.org/) plugin that automatically wraps CSS in [@layer](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/@layer) based on the file path.

## Why

[CSS Cascade Layers](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn_web_development/Core/Styling_basics/Cascade_layers) let you explicitly control specificity by grouping styles into named layers. Maintaining `@layer` wrappers manually across dozens of files is tedious and error-prone. This plugin detects the layer from the file's path automatically — keeping your source files clean while the build output is correctly layered.

## Install

```bash
npm i -D postcss-auto-layer

yarn add -D postcss-auto-layer

pnpm add -D postcss-auto-layer

bun add -d postcss-auto-layer
```

## Usage

### PostCSS config

```js
// postcss.config.js
import postcssAutoLayer from "postcss-auto-layer";

export default {
  plugins: [
    postcssAutoLayer({
      layers: ["app", "pages", "widgets", "features", "entities", "shared"],
      skipPatterns: [/\/shared\/styles\//],
    }),
  ],
};
```

### Vite

```ts
// vite.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from "vite";
import postcssAutoLayer from "postcss-auto-layer";

export default defineConfig({
  css: {
    postcss: {
      plugins: [
        postcssAutoLayer({
          layers: ["app", "pages", "widgets", "features", "entities", "shared"],
        }),
      ],
    },
  },
});
```

### Next.js

```js
// postcss.config.mjs
const config = {
  plugins: {
    "postcss-auto-layer": {
      layers: [
        "app",
        "layouts",
        "views",
        "widgets",
        "features",
        "entities",
        "shared",
      ],
    },
  },
};

export default config;
```

### Example

**Input** (`src/features/auth/styles.css`):

```css
.login-form {
  display: flex;
}
.login-form__input {
  border: 1px solid #ccc;
}
```

**Output**:

```css
@layer features {
  .login-form {
    display: flex;
  }
  .login-form__input {
    border: 1px solid #ccc;
  }
}
```

### How layer detection works

The plugin scans the file path for the first segment matching a name from `layers`. For example:

| File path                         | Detected layer         |
| --------------------------------- | ---------------------- |
| `src/features/auth/styles.css`    | `features`             |
| `src/shared/ui/button.css`        | `shared`               |
| `node_modules/some-lib/index.css` | `vendor`               |
| `src/main.css`                    | _(none — not wrapped)_ |

Files from `node_modules` are always placed in the `vendor` layer regardless of the `layers` option. Files with no matching segment are left untouched. Windows paths (`C:\project\src\features\...`) are normalized automatically.

## Setting up layer order

The cascade order of `@layer` is determined by the first time each layer name appears in your CSS. To make the order explicit and predictable, add a layer order declaration to your global stylesheet:

```css
/* src/app/styles/global.css */
@layer vendor, shared, entities, features, widgets, pages, app;
```

The plugin leaves bare `@layer` order declarations (those without a block body) at the top level, so they won't be re-wrapped.

## Options

```ts
interface PluginOptions {
  /**
   * Layer names to detect from the file path.
   * @example ['app', 'pages', 'widgets', 'features', 'entities', 'shared']
   */
  layers: string[];

  /**
   * Patterns of file paths that should be skipped entirely (not wrapped).
   * @default []
   */
  skipPatterns?: RegExp[];
}
```

## Features

- `@charset` **and** `@import` are never wrapped — they must remain at the top level of a stylesheet.
- **Empty** `@layer` **declarations** (e.g., `@layer app, shared;`) are also left at the top level so the cascade order is preserved.
- **Already-wrapped files** (the entire CSS is already inside a single `@layer` block) are left untouched to prevent double-wrapping.
- `node_modules` files are placed in `vendor` layer by default.

## TypeScript

The package ships with full TypeScript declarations. Import the `PluginOptions` type if needed:

```ts
import postcssAutoLayer, { type PluginOptions } from "postcss-auto-layer";
```

